---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import SessionGrid from '../../../../../components/SessionGrid.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';
import TagList from '../../../../../components/TagList.astro';

const registrations = `builder.Services.AddSingleton<AppClock>();
builder.Services.AddScoped<RequestAudit>();
builder.Services.AddTransient<SlugFormatter>();`;

const endpoint = `app.MapPost("/orders", (
    CreateOrderRequest request,
    OrderDbContext db,
    RequestAudit audit,
    SlugFormatter slugs) =>
{
    audit.Mark("creating order");

    var slug = slugs.FromTitle(request.Title);
    // db participates in this request's unit of work

    return Results.Created($"/orders/{slug}", new { slug });
});`;

const badSingleton = `public sealed class CurrentUserCache
{
    public string? UserId { get; set; }
}

builder.Services.AddSingleton<CurrentUserCache>(); // dangerous`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 4 · Service lifetimes"
  heading="Service lifetimes: how long should this object live?"
  lede="Today’s win: choose Singleton, Scoped, or Transient by asking what state the object is allowed to remember."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="Correction anchor">
    <Callout>
      You were right to challenge the previous follow-up: the session code used <code>builder.Services.AddSingleton&lt;AppClock&gt;();</code>. So <code>AppClock</code> was registered as a singleton. The handler still did not create it. The DI container creates one <code>AppClock</code> and reuses it.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The first-principles question">
    <p>
      Dependency injection answers “who creates this object?” Lifetimes answer the next question: “how long does the created object stay alive?”
    </p>
    <p>
      Do not memorize the names first. Ask what would break if the same instance were reused too long, or if a fresh instance were created too often.
    </p>
    <TagList tags={['same for app', 'same for request', 'new when asked']} />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The three default lifetimes">
    <SessionGrid>
      <div>
        <h3>Singleton</h3>
        <p>One instance for the whole app lifetime. Good for stateless services, app-wide caches, clocks, and configuration-shaped services.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Scoped</h3>
        <p>One instance per request scope. Good for database contexts, unit-of-work objects, request audit state, and request-specific data.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Transient</h3>
        <p>A new instance each time it is requested. Good for lightweight helpers where identity and stored state do not matter.</p>
      </div>
    </SessionGrid>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Registration syntax">
    <p>
      The method name chooses the lifetime. The type name chooses what the container can provide.
    </p>
    <Code code={registrations} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Backend mental model">
    <p>
      Imagine a request that creates an order. The handler asks for three helpers. The container decides whether each helper is reused globally, reused inside this request, or freshly created.
    </p>
    <Code code={endpoint} lang="csharp" />
    <ul>
      <li><code>OrderDbContext</code> should usually be <strong>scoped</strong>: one request, one unit of work.</li>
      <li><code>RequestAudit</code> should be <strong>scoped</strong>: it records facts about this request, not every user’s request.</li>
      <li><code>SlugFormatter</code> can be <strong>transient</strong> if it is a tiny stateless formatter.</li>
      <li><code>AppClock</code> can be <strong>singleton</strong> if it only wraps time/options and stores no per-request user data.</li>
    </ul>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The common dangerous mistake">
    <p>
      A singleton must not store per-request mutable state. If it remembers the current user, current request, or current database transaction, that state can leak between requests.
    </p>
    <Code code={badSingleton} lang="csharp" />
    <Callout>
      Rule of thumb: if the object says “current request,” “current user,” “current tenant,” or “current transaction,” be suspicious of <code>Singleton</code>.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Checkpoint">
    <p>
      Reply in Discord with three lines. Choose <strong>Singleton</strong>, <strong>Scoped</strong>, or <strong>Transient</strong>, and give one sentence why:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><code>PricingRules</code>: reads fixed rules loaded at startup; no per-request state.</li>
      <li><code>OrderDbContext</code>: tracks database changes while one HTTP request runs.</li>
      <li><code>EmailSubjectFormatter</code>: tiny stateless string helper.</li>
    </ol>
  </SessionSection>
</SessionPage>
